title: Appointment to the Expert Committee on Food Safety (with photo)
content_text:
p>
The Government announced today (September 14) the appointment of Professor Kwan 
Hoi-shan as the Chairman of the Expert Committee on Food Safety. The appointment was made by the Secretary for Health, Welfare and Food, Dr York 
Chow. Professor Kwan will serve a term of two years with effect from tomorrow 
(September 15). Professor Kwan is the Dean of the Faculty of Science and Professor of Biology of 
the Chinese University of Hong Kong. He is a well-established academic in food 
and nutritional science specialising in food science, food microbiology and

and nutritional science specialising in food science, food microbiology and 
molecular biotechnology.  A Government spokesman said, "The Committee is to advise the Director of Food 
and Environmental Hygiene on food safety operational strategies and measures to 
protect public health, standards/guidelines relating to food safety and food 
composition and their suitable adoption in Hong Kong. "The Committee also advises on the implementation of food safety risk 
communication and public education programmes as well as new directions for

communication and public education programmes as well as new directions for research to be commissioned by the Centre for Food Safety." Welcoming the appointment, the Director of Food and Environmental Hygiene, Mr Eddy Chan, said that Professor Kwan's experience and expertise made him most suitable for the chairmanship of the committee. Representative of the Department of Health Apart from the above appointments, Dr Chow also appointed three experts from the Mainland and overseas as members of the committee. They are Dr Kan Xuegui from the Mainland, Dr Chua Sin-bin from Singapore and Dr Marion Joy Healy from Australia. Educated on the Mainland, in Canada and the United Kingdom, Dr Kan Xuegui is a medical doctor by profession who specialises in infectious diseases, public

medical doctor by profession who specialises in infectious diseases, public 
health and public health management. He is a Consultant in the Bureau of Health 
Supervision of the Ministry of Health of the People's Republic of China.  Dr Chua Sin-bin is the Chief Executive Officer, Director-General and Chief 
Veterinary Officer of the Agri-Food and Veterinary Authority of Singapore.  Dr Marion Joy Healy is the Chief Scientist of the Food Standards Australia New 
Zealand (FSANZ) and has overall responsibility for the scientific work

Zealand (FSANZ) and has overall responsibility for the scientific work undertaken by FSANZ as well as for the organisation's input into the international regulatory framework such as Codex. All members will serve a term of two years with effect from tomorrow (September 15). Ends/Thursday, September 14, 2006
